Title

Latent Supervision: A Mathematical Framework for Dual-Cognitive Architectures in Real-Time Digital Agents

---

Abstract

This thesis presents a mathematical foundation for dual-cognitive architectures that separate reflexive execution from deliberative planning across heterogeneous compute substrates. We introduce Project Janus, a theoretical framework comprising two specialized minds: Janus-Praeter, a fast edge-deployed system for real-time interaction, and Janus-Futurus, a slow cloud-based system for deep reasoning. The core contribution is a formal model of Latent Supervision, wherein strategic guidance is transmitted as dense vectors rather than symbolic commands, enabling tight coupling without breaking the real-time loop. We develop mathematical formulations for: (1) an uncertainty-driven gating mechanism based on predictive entropy, (2) a communication protocol for transmitting compressed state and latent instructions, and (3) an asynchronous distillation process that transfers knowledge from cloud to edge. We prove bounds on the system's autonomy ratio and derive conditions under which the architecture achieves optimal trade-offs between latency, cost, and capability. This work establishes a rigorous theoretical basis for designing real-time digital agents that combine the speed of edge inference with the intelligence of cloud-scale models.

