Chapter 2: Related Theoretical Work

2.1 Models of Dual Cognition in AI

The concept of dual-process cognition originates in psychology, where System 1 is fast, automatic, and intuitive, while System 2 is slow, deliberate, and analytical. In AI, this has inspired architectures like Fast and Slow (Schmidhuber, 2022) and mixture-of-experts models. However, existing work assumes homogeneous compute; Janus is novel in explicitly modeling heterogeneous hardware with different cost-latency profiles.

2.2 Uncertainty Estimation in Neural Networks

Theoretical foundations for uncertainty in deep learning include Bayesian neural networks (Neal, 1996), Monte Carlo dropout (Gal & Ghahramani, 2016), and deep ensembles (Lakshminarayanan et al., 2017). For sequential decision-making, predictive entropy of the action distribution has been used as a measure of epistemic uncertainty (Pathak et al., 2019). We build on this by formalizing entropy-based gating as a solution to the exploration-exploitation trade-off extended to the cloud-edge setting.

2.3 Information Theory and Compression

Rate-distortion theory (Cover & Thomas, 2006) provides a foundation for compressing state representations while preserving task-relevant information. The Janus-Link Protocol can be viewed as a rate-distortion problem where we minimize transmitted bits subject to a bound on task performance degradation.

2.4 Hierarchical Reinforcement Learning

Hierarchical RL (Sutton et al., 1999) decomposes complex tasks into sub-tasks, with higher-level policies setting goals for lower-level policies. Janus-Futurus can be seen as a high-level policy that issues latent goals to Janus-Praeter, but with the crucial difference that the high-level policy runs on different hardware and is invoked only when needed.

2.5 Knowledge Distillation

Knowledge distillation (Hinton et al., 2015) transfers knowledge from a large teacher model to a small student. Janus's asynchronous distillation extends this to an online setting where the teacher is intermittently available and the student continually improves.

2.6 Research Gap

No existing theoretical framework unifies these elements into a coherent model of heterogeneous dual-cognitive systems with explicit cost-latency trade-offs and formal guarantees. This thesis fills that gap.

