Chapter 3: The Janus Mathematical Framework

3.1 Formal Definitions

Let a digital environment be defined as a tuple $\mathcal{E} = (\mathcal{O}, \mathcal{A}, \mathcal{T}, \mathcal{R}, \gamma)$ where:

· $\mathcal{O}$ is the observation space (screen state, events)
· $\mathcal{A}$ is the action space
· $\mathcal{T}: \mathcal{O} \times \mathcal{A} \rightarrow \mathcal{O}$ is the transition function
· $\mathcal{R}: \mathcal{O} \times \mathcal{A} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ is the reward function
· $\gamma \in [0,1]$ is the discount factor

A goal $g \in \mathcal{G}$ is a specification of desired outcomes, which induces a reward function $\mathcal{R}_g$.

A policy $\pi: \mathcal{O}^* \rightarrow \mathcal{A}$ maps observation histories to actions.

3.2 Janus-Praeter: The Edge Model

Janus-Praeter is a policy $\pi_p: \mathcal{O}^k \times \mathcal{G} \rightarrow \mathcal{A}$ that operates on the last $k$ observations (a fixed-size history). It has a maximum permissible latency $L_{max}$ and a finite computational budget $B$.

We model $\pi_p$ as a function approximator with parameters $\theta_p$, producing a distribution over actions:

\pi_p(a | o_{t-k:t}, g) = \text{softmax}(f_{\theta_p}(o_{t-k:t}, g))

The predictive entropy at time $t$ is:

H_t = -\sum_{a \in \mathcal{A}} \pi_p(a | o_{t-k:t}, g) \log \pi_p(a | o_{t-k:t}, g)

3.3 Janus-Futurus: The Cloud Model

Janus-Futurus is a policy $\pi_f: \mathcal{O}^* \times \mathcal{G} \rightarrow \mathcal{A}^*$ that can reason over full histories and generate multi-step plans. It has effectively unlimited computational resources but incurs cost $c_f$ per query and latency $l_f \gg L_{max}$.

Crucially, $\pi_f$ does not output actions directly when queried by Praeter. Instead, it outputs a Latent Guidance Vector (LGV) $z \in \mathbb{R}^d$ that encodes strategic information.

Formally, given a compressed state representation $s_t$ from Praeter and goal $g$, Futurus computes:

z = \phi_f(s_t, g)

where $\phi_f$ is a function derived from the internal representations of $\pi_f$.

3.4 The Janus Router

The Router monitors $H_t$ and decides whether to query Futurus. A gating policy $\pi_g: \mathbb{R}_{\geq0} \rightarrow \{0,1\}$ maps current entropy to a binary decision.

Let $g_t = \pi_g(H_t)$ indicate whether a query is made at time $t$. The system dynamics become:

a_t = \begin{cases} 
\pi_p(o_{t-k:t}, g) & \text{if } g_t = 0 \\
\pi_p(o_{t-k:t}, g, z_{t-1}) & \text{if } g_t = 1 \text{ and } z_{t-1} \text{ is available}
\end{cases}

where $z_{t-1}$ is the LGV from the most recent query.

3.5 The Janus-Link Protocol

When a query is triggered, Praeter compresses its observation history into a state packet $s_t$. This is a function $\psi: \mathcal{O}^k \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^m$ with $m \ll |\mathcal{O}^k|$.

We require that $\psi$ preserves sufficient information for Futurus to generate useful guidance. Formally, for any two histories $h_1, h_2$ that are distinguishable under the optimal policy, we want $D_{KL}(\pi_f(\cdot | h_1, g) || \pi_f(\cdot | h_2, g))$ to be bounded below by some function of $||\psi(h_1) - \psi(h_2)||$.

3.6 Latent Instruction Injection

Upon receiving $z$, Praeter incorporates it via a modified policy:

\pi_p(a | o_{t-k:t}, g, z) = \text{softmax}(f_{\theta_p}(o_{t-k:t}, g, z))

where $z$ is injected into the model's intermediate layers, typically via cross-attention.

We model this as a conditional policy where $z$ modulates the base distribution:

\pi_p(a | o, g, z) \propto \pi_p(a | o, g) \cdot \exp(\text{score}(a, z))

3.7 Asynchronous Distillation

After each successful episode, we store the trajectory $\tau = (o_1, a_1, \dots, o_T, a_T)$ along with any LGVs $z_{t_1}, \dots, z_{t_q}$ received during the episode.

Periodically, we update $\theta_p$ by minimizing:

\mathcal{L}(\theta_p) = \mathcal{L}_{\text{action}}(\tau) + \lambda \mathcal{L}_{\text{latent}}(\tau)

where $\mathcal{L}_{\text{action}}$ is the standard negative log-likelihood of actions, and $\mathcal{L}_{\text{latent}}$ encourages Praeter's internal representations to match the LGVs when similar states are encountered.

