Chapter 7: Metrics and Evaluation Framework

7.1 Formal Metrics

Define the Triple-A Score for a system $S$ on task distribution $\mathcal{T}$:

· Autonomy Ratio: $A_r(S) = \mathbb{E}_{\mathcal{T}}[\frac{T_{\text{local}}}{T_{\text{total}}}]$
· Latency-to-Success: $L_s(S) = \mathbb{E}_{\mathcal{T}}[\sum_{t=1}^T l_t]$ where $l_t$ is per-step latency
· Recovery Efficiency: $R_e(S) = \mathbb{E}_{\mathcal{T}}[\frac{\text{steps after LGV before next query}}{\text{total cloud queries}}]$

7.2 The Optimal Switching Frontier

For a family of systems parameterized by trade-off parameter $\beta$, we define the Optimal Switching Frontier (OSF) as the Pareto-optimal curve in the space of (Cost, Latency, Success Rate).

Theorem 7.1 (OSF Characterization). For Janus with optimal gating and distillation, the OSF is convex and its shape is determined by the joint distribution of task difficulty and state transition entropy.

7.3 Benchmark Design Principles

We propose design criteria for evaluating dual-cognitive systems:

1. Difficulty Stratification: Tasks must span routine, dynamic, and adversarial categories.
2. Cost Accounting: Must track both monetary cost (cloud queries) and time cost (latency).
3. Generalization Testing: Must include held-out tasks to measure transfer.
4. Long-Term Learning: Must evaluate improvement over repeated episodes.

